# Jump Hippo — release signing & notarization environment
#
# Credentials for SIGNED local installer builds (`make dist-mac` / `make
# dist-win` / `make sign-dmg`). Copy this file to `release.env` (git-ignored) and
# fill in the values for the platform you are building on:
#
#   cp release.env.example release.env
#
# The Makefile `-include`s release.env and `export`s these names, so a local
# `make dist-*` picks them up the same way `make debug` reads dev.env. In CI the
# SAME variable names are supplied from repository secrets (see the Release
# workflow, .github/workflows/release.yml), never from this file. Push the local
# values up as GitHub Actions secrets with `make sync-mac` / `make sync-win`.
#
# Everything here is OPTIONAL: with no release.env (and no secrets in CI), the
# build still succeeds — electron-builder simply emits UNSIGNED artifacts and
# skips notarization. Never commit real values; release.env stays local only.

# ── macOS — Developer ID signing ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Export your "Developer ID Application" cert + private key as a .p12, then
# base64-encode it for CSC_LINK (or point CSC_LINK at the .p12 file path):
#   base64 -i DeveloperID.p12 | pbcopy
# Leave these blank to fall back to a Developer ID identity already installed in
# your login keychain (CSC_IDENTITY_AUTO_DISCOVERY must then stay unset/true).
CSC_LINK=
CSC_KEY_PASSWORD=

# Set to false to force-skip macOS code signing (handy for a quick unsigned
# dist). Leave unset to let electron-builder auto-discover / use CSC_LINK.
# CSC_IDENTITY_AUTO_DISCOVERY=false

# ── macOS — notarization (Apple notarytool) ───────────────────────────────────
# Option A (simplest) — Apple ID + app-specific password + team id. Generate the
# app-specific password at https://appleid.apple.com → Sign-In and Security.
APPLE_ID=
APPLE_APP_SPECIFIC_PASSWORD=
APPLE_TEAM_ID=

# Option B (recommended for CI) — App Store Connect API key. APPLE_API_KEY is the
# path to the downloaded AuthKey_XXXXXXXXXX.p8 file. Use EITHER option A or B.
# APPLE_API_KEY=
# APPLE_API_KEY_ID=
# APPLE_API_ISSUER=

# ── Windows — Authenticode signing ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Base64-encode your code-signing .pfx for WIN_CSC_LINK (or give a file path):
#   base64 -i codesign.pfx | pbcopy
# (In CI, Windows exes can instead be signed by SignPath Foundation — see the
# Release workflow header; that path needs repo vars/secrets, not these.)
WIN_CSC_LINK=
WIN_CSC_KEY_PASSWORD=

# ── Microsoft Store (appx) — Partner Center identity ──────────────────────────
# Reserve the app name in Partner Center, then copy its "Product identity" values
# here (or into build.appx in src/package.json). `make dist-appx` graceful-skips
# when these are unset. The Store re-signs the package on upload, so no cert is
# needed. See STORE-PUBLISHING.md.
APPX_IDENTITY_NAME=
APPX_PUBLISHER=
APPX_PUBLISHER_DISPLAY_NAME=

# ── Mac App Store provisioning profiles are FILES, not env vars ───────────────
# Download them from the Apple Developer portal and drop them at:
#   src/packaging/embedded.provisionprofile      (distribution → make dist-mas)
#   src/packaging/development.provisionprofile   (development  → make mas-dev)
# Both are git-ignored. The MAS signing certs (Apple Distribution + Mac Installer
# Distribution) live in your login keychain. See STORE-PUBLISHING.md.

# ── GitHub — release publishing ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# electron-builder's `--publish` uploads to the GitHub Release for jfigge/jumphippo.
# Locally this is only needed for a manual publish; CI provides GITHUB_TOKEN. Use a
# token with `repo` scope (e.g. `gh auth token`). `make sync-mac`/`sync-win` use the
# `gh` CLI's own auth, not this value.
# GH_TOKEN=
